<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="321" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1437,258,1978]" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1557,1582]" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Molineri &amp; Salles, 2017" authorityName="Molineri &amp; Salles" authorityYear="2017" box="[328,557,1558,1581]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="321" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pereirae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[328,557,1558,1581]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">Campsurus pereirae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[565,655,1557,1582]" pageId="20" pageNumber="321" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[565,655,1557,1582]" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
is known from adults of both sexes, and it can be distinguished from other species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Eaton" authorityYear="1868" box="[332,459,1594,1617]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="321" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[332,459,1594,1617]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">Campsurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by: 1) posterior margin of male abdominal sternum IX truncate (
<figureCitation box="[1182,1264,1593,1618]" captionStart="FIGURES 68 – 76" captionStartId="18.[151,264,1825,1848]" captionTargetBox="[265,1305,209,1801]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[260,1326,193,1805]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 68 – 76. Male adults. Campsurus zunigae sp. nov.: 68, genitalia of imago, v. v.; 69, genitalia of subimago, l. v.; 70, detail of penes of imago, l. v. Campsurus pereirae sp. nov., imago: 71, genitalia, v. v.; 72, detail of pedestal, v. v.; 73, detail of penes, v. v.; 74, genitalia, l. v. (forceps omitted). Campsurus janae sp. nov., imago: 75, genitalia, v. v.: 76, detail of penes, l. v." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/838452/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">Fig. 71</figureCitation>
); 2) pedestal of each side touching basally, with apically acute parastylus (
<figureCitation box="[812,896,1629,1654]" captionStart="FIGURES 68 – 76" captionStartId="18.[151,264,1825,1848]" captionTargetBox="[265,1305,209,1801]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[260,1326,193,1805]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 68 – 76. Male adults. Campsurus zunigae sp. nov.: 68, genitalia of imago, v. v.; 69, genitalia of subimago, l. v.; 70, detail of penes of imago, l. v. Campsurus pereirae sp. nov., imago: 71, genitalia, v. v.; 72, detail of pedestal, v. v.; 73, detail of penes, v. v.; 74, genitalia, l. v. (forceps omitted). Campsurus janae sp. nov., imago: 75, genitalia, v. v.: 76, detail of penes, l. v." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/838452/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">Fig. 72</figureCitation>
), round inner corner strongly projected; 3) base of main lobe of penes sclerotized, strongly expanded laterally and proximally with its dorsal surface finely granulated (
<figureCitation box="[285,368,1701,1726]" captionStart="FIGURES 68 – 76" captionStartId="18.[151,264,1825,1848]" captionTargetBox="[265,1305,209,1801]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[260,1326,193,1805]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 68 – 76. Male adults. Campsurus zunigae sp. nov.: 68, genitalia of imago, v. v.; 69, genitalia of subimago, l. v.; 70, detail of penes of imago, l. v. Campsurus pereirae sp. nov., imago: 71, genitalia, v. v.; 72, detail of pedestal, v. v.; 73, detail of penes, v. v.; 74, genitalia, l. v. (forceps omitted). Campsurus janae sp. nov., imago: 75, genitalia, v. v.: 76, detail of penes, l. v." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/838452/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">Fig. 73</figureCitation>
), apical 1/3 narrowing abruptly, rounded and slightly curved ventrally; secondary membranous lobe cylindrical and slender; 4) small size (length of male fore wings 6.5–7.0 mm); 5) female socket single, subquadrate (
<figureCitation box="[301,385,1773,1798]" captionStart="FIGURES 85 – 93" captionStartId="24.[151,264,1909,1932]" captionTargetBox="[168,1418,342,1885]" captionTargetId="figure@24.[163,1418,337,1885]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURES 85 – 93. Campsurus povilla sp. nov., male imago: 85, genitalia, v. v.; 86, detail of pedestals, v. v.; 87, detail of penes, v. v. Nymph: 88, left mandibular tusk, detail of inner tubercles; 89, left mandible, occlusal view (the basal part and molae were displaced during slide preparation; 90, same, detail of apex; 91, right mandible, occlusal view. Female abdominal sternum VIII with detail of socket: 92, C. povilla sp. nov.; 93, C. zunigae sp. nov." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/838456/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">Fig. 93</figureCitation>
); 6) egg with large polar cap, ratio maximum width of egg/width of PC =1.4.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="321" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1437,258,1978]" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,1809,1834]" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">Discussion.</emphasis>
The extremely expanded penes and the fine granules present on them are unique to 
<taxonomicName authority="Molineri &amp; Salles, 2017" authorityName="Molineri &amp; Salles" authorityYear="2017" box="[1269,1396,1810,1833]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="321" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pereirae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1269,1396,1810,1833]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">C. pereirae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="20" pageNumber="321" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
, distinguishing this species from the closely related 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Traver ." authorityYear="1947" box="[810,977,1846,1869]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="321" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cuyuniensis">
<emphasis box="[810,977,1846,1869]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">C. cuyuniensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Molineri &amp; Salles, 2017" authorityName="Molineri &amp; Salles" authorityYear="2017" box="[994,1149,1846,1869]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="321" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nessimiani" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[994,1149,1846,1869]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">C. nessimiani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1159,1251,1845,1870]" pageId="20" pageNumber="321" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1159,1251,1845,1870]" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Molineri &amp; Salles, 2017" authorityName="Molineri &amp; Salles" authorityYear="2017" box="[1268,1393,1845,1870]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="321" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dasilvai" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1268,1393,1845,1870]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">C. dasilvai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="20" pageNumber="321" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Molineri &amp; Salles, 2017" authorityName="Molineri &amp; Salles" authorityYear="2017" box="[215,337,1882,1905]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="321" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zunigae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[215,337,1882,1905]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">C. zunigae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[345,436,1881,1906]" pageId="20" pageNumber="321" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[345,436,1881,1906]" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Molineri &amp; Salles, 2017" authorityName="Molineri &amp; Salles" authorityYear="2017" box="[493,590,1882,1905]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="321" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="janae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[493,590,1882,1905]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">C. janae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[598,689,1881,1906]" pageId="20" pageNumber="321" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[598,689,1881,1906]" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
<taxonomicName authority="Molineri &amp; Salles, 2017" authorityName="Molineri &amp; Salles" authorityYear="2017" box="[698,896,1882,1905]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="321" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="janae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[698,896,1882,1905]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">Campsurus janae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[905,996,1881,1906]" pageId="20" pageNumber="321" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[905,996,1881,1906]" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
also presents penes with an extremely wide base, but the penes are smooth, and the pedestals are much larger and shorter than in 
<taxonomicName authority="Molineri &amp; Salles, 2017" authorityName="Molineri &amp; Salles" authorityYear="2017" box="[1206,1335,1918,1941]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="321" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pereirae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1206,1335,1918,1941]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">C. pereirae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1344,1436,1917,1942]" pageId="20" pageNumber="321" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1344,1436,1917,1942]" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
Again, the finely granulated penes are unique to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Molineri &amp; Salles" authorityYear="2017" box="[696,823,1954,1977]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="321" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pereirae">
<emphasis box="[696,823,1954,1977]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="321">C. pereirae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
